"1311–1372":"1311–1372","1312–1365":"1312–1365","1338":"1338","about 1338":"circa 1338","1455":"1455","1312":"1312","1334":"1334","1311":"1311","1365":"1365","1420":"1420","1372":"1372","1360":"1360","1382":"1382","Moretonhampstead, Devon, England":"Moretonhampstead, Devon, England","Devon, England":"Devon, England"},"en":{"about 1338–":"about 1338–Deceased","1338–Female":"1338–Deceased","1334–Male":"1334–Deceased","1360–1420":"1360–1420","1311–1372":"1311–1372","1312–1365":"1312–1365","1338":"1338","about 1338":"about 1338","1455":"1455","1312":"1312","1334":"1334","1311":"1311","1365":"1365","1420":"1420","1372":"1372","1360":"1360","1382":"1382","Moretonhampstead, Devon, England":"Moretonhampstead, Devon, England","Devon, England":"Devon, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Lehman","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Americanized form of German   Lehmann  . Compare   Layman  ,   Leaman  ,   Leeman  , and   Leman  .","Jewish (Ashkenazic): variant of   Lehmann  .","History: This (see 1 above) is the name of a Swiss Mennonite family, originating in the Emmental in the canton of Bern, Switzerland, from where many of its bearers moved in the early 18th century to the Palatinate in Germany, Alsace in France, and (finally) to PA in the US. Its original Swiss German form is <i>Lehmann</i>. Among the American Mennonites it is also established in the altered forms <i>Layman</i> and <i>Leaman</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Lhamon","meanings":["Altered form of German   Lehman  ."]},{"name":"Lehmann","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Heinz, Hans, Otto, Erwin, Fritz, Klaus, Gerhard, Arno, Gunter, Juergen, Almut.","German: status name for a feudal tenant or vassal, Middle High German <i>lēheman</i>, <i>lēnman</i> (from <i>lēhen</i> ‘to hold land as a feudal tenant’ + <i>man</i> ‘man’). The tenant held land on loan for the duration of his life in return for rent or service, but was not free to transfer or divide it. See also   Lehman  .","Jewish (western Ashkenazic): from the personal name <i>Lehmann</i>, perhaps related to   Leo   3."]}]},{"name":"Laura","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Feminine form of the Late Latin male name <i>Laurus</i> ‘laurel’.  St Laura  was a 9th-century Spanish nun who met her death in a cauldron of molten lead. Laura is also the name of the woman addressed in the love poetry of the Italian poet  Petrarch  (  Francesco Petrarca ,  1304–74 ), and it owes much of its subsequent popularity to this. There have been various speculations about her identity, but it has not been established with any certainty. He first met her in  1327  while living in Avignon, and she died of the plague in  1348 . The popularity of the given name in the English-speaking world has endured since the 19th century, when it was probably imported from Italy."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Selma","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Of uncertain origin, probably a contracted form of   Selima .  It has also been occasionally used in Germany and Scandinavia, probably because it occurs as the name of Ossian's castle in Macpherson's ballads."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":44,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705197,"age":117,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Baroness Laura Selma Lehman was born about 1338, in Devon, England, her father, Henry Lehman, was 28 and her mother, Elizabeth Bertson, was 27. She had at least 1 daughter with Herman Tucker."},"et":{"about 1338–":"umbes 1338–Surnud","1338–Female":"1338–Surnud","1334–Male":"1334–Surnud","1360–1420":"1360–1420","1311–1372":"1311–1372","1312–1365":"1312–1365","1338":"1338","about 1338":"umbes 1338","1455":"1455","1312":"1312","1334":"1334","1311":"1311","1365":"1365","1420":"1420","1372":"1372","1360":"1360","1382":"1382","Moretonhampstead, Devon, England":"Moretonhampstead, Devon, England","Devon, England":"Devon, England"},"fi":{"about 1338–":"noin 1338–Kuollut","1338–Female":"1338–Kuollut","1334–Male":"1334–Kuollut","1360–1420":"1360–1420","1311–1372":"1311–1372","1312–1365":"1312–1365","1338":"1338","about 1338":"noin 1338","1455":"1455","1312":"1312","1334":"1334","1311":"1311","1365":"1365","1420":"1420","1372":"1372","1360":"1360","1382":"1382","Moretonhampstead, Devon, England":"Moretonhampstead, Devon, England","Devon, England":"Devon, England"},"fr":{"about 1338–":"environ 1338–Décédée","1338–Female":"1338–Décédée","1334–Male":"1334–Décédé","1360–1420":"1360–1420","1311–1372":"1311–1372","1312–1365":"1312–1365","1338":"1338","about 1338":"environ 1338","1455":"1455","1312":"1312","1334":"1334","1311":"1311","1365":"1365","1420":"1420","1372":"1372","1360":"1360","1382":"1382","Moretonhampstead, Devon, England":"Moretonhampstead, Devon, Angleterre","Devon, England":"Devon, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Baroness Laura Selma Lehman est née environ 1338, à Devon, Angleterre, son père,